HEADWORD: Desirable
<hw>De*sir"a*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>d⟦eacute⟧sirable</ets>, fr. L. <ets>desiderabilis</ets>. See
<er>Desire</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>Worthy of desire or
longing; fitted to excite desire or a wish to possess; pleasing;
agreeable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All of them <qex>desirable</qex> young men.</q> <rj><qau>Ezek.
xxiii. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As things <qex>desirable</qex> excite⟦br⟧
Desire, and objects move the appetite.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackmore.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Desirableness</ent>⟦br⟧
